  "prompt": "How can I use markdown with django?",
  "response": "To use Markdown with Django, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. Install a Markdown library:\n```bash\npip install markdown\n```\n\n2. In your Django view or model method:\n```python\nimport markdown\n\ndef convert_markdown_to_html(markdown_text):\n    return markdown.markdown(markdown_text)\n```\n\n3. In a template, you can create a custom template filter:\n```python\n# In your app's templatetags/markdown_extras.py\nfrom django import template\nimport markdown\nimport bleach  # Optional: for sanitizing HTML\n\nregister = template.Library()\n\n@register.filter\ndef markdown_to_html(text):\n    # Optional: sanitize the HTML to prevent XSS\n    return bleach.clean(markdown.markdown(text, extensions=['extra']))\n```\n\n4. In your template:\n```html\n{% load markdown_extras %}\n\n{{ post.content|markdown_to_html|safe }}\n```\n\n5. For a more robust solution, you can use django-markdownify:\n```bash\npip install django-markdownify\n```\n\nConfiguration in settings.py:\n```python\nINSTALLED_APPS = [\n    ...\n    'markdownify',\n]\n\nMARKDOWNIFY_MARKDOWN_EXTENSIONS = ['extra']\nMARKDOWNIFY_BLEACH_ALLOWED_TAGS = ['p', 'h1', 'h2', 'h3', 'h4', 'h5', 'h6', 'pre', 'code']\n```\n\nIn your template:\n```html\n{% load markdownify %}\n\n{{ post.content|markdownify }}\n```\n\n6. Another option is django-markdown-deux:\n```bash\npip install markdown2 django-markdown-deux\n```\n\nConfiguration:\n```python\nINSTALLED_APPS = [\n    ...\n    'markdown_deux',\n]\n```\n\nIn template:\n```html\n{% load markdown_deux_tags %}\n\n{{ post.content|markdown2 }}\n```\n\nAdvanced Example with More Configuration:\n```python\n# models.py\nfrom django.db import models\nimport markdown\n\nclass Post(models.Model):\n    title = models.CharField(max_length=200)\n    content = models.TextField()\n    \n    def get_markdown_content(self):\n        # Custom markdown processing\n        return markdown.markdown(\n            self.content, \n            extensions=[\n                'extra',  # Adds support for tables, footnotes, etc.\n                'codehilite',  # Code syntax highlighting\n                'toc',  # Table of contents\n            ],\n            extension_configs={\n                'codehilite': {\n                    'css_class': 'highlight'\n                }\n            }\n        )\n\n# views.py\ndef post_detail(request, post_id):\n    post = Post.objects.get(id=post_id)\n    return render(request, 'post_detail.html', {\n        'post': post,\n        'markdown_content': post.get_markdown_content()\n    })\n```\n\nBest Practices:\n1. Always use `|safe` filter when rendering markdown-converted HTML\n2. Consider using Bleach for HTML sanitization\n3. Choose markdown extensions based on your needs\n4. Handle potential markdown parsing errors\n\nPerformance Tip:\nFor frequently accessed content, consider caching the markdown-to-HTML conversion:\n\n```python\nfrom django.core.cache import cache\n\ndef get_cached_markdown(text):\n    cache_key = f'markdown_{hash(text)}'\n    cached_html = cache.get(cache_key)\n    \n    if not cached_html:\n        cached_html = markdown.markdown(text)\n        cache.set(cache_key, cached_html, 3600)  # Cache for 1 hour\n    \n    return cached_html\n```\n\nEach approach has pros and cons, so choose the one that best fits your project's requirements. The built-in markdown library with a custom template filter is often the most straightforward solution for most Django projects.",
